He is making one of his usual plays on the man’s cognomen Ligur, which was also the name of a Ligurian. C. F. Hermann in Vind. Lat. ep. ad Brutum, p. 31 (quoted by Halm), explains ‘quo magis,’ διο. thus: “quo tamen nihil am- plius effecit quam ut qui id cognomen audi- rent, natione Ligurem, non Aeliorum cog- natum existimarent.'’ This is a true ex- planation. The form of the Latin sentence may be elliptical. As it stands ‘ quo . . . videretur ’ does not express a purpose, but a consequence. We can say in a few words, and they express the full meaning, “by stealing a cognomen from the busts of the Aelii he got the reputation of belonging to the (Ligurian) nation, and not to the (Aelian) faniily.”
